            "author_info": {
                "name": "Karl Baxter",
                "href": "/profile/Karl-Baxter-2"
            },
            "answer_text": "I may make myself unpopular here but by the time Live Aid came along Queen were way past their prime. Having grown up with them I felt their best years were up to about 1980 - after which they were mediocre at best. This wasn\u2019t helped that the LP \u201cQueen\u2019s Greatest Hits\u201d distilled all their hits but left out all the more out-of-character album tracks that might have diluted their legacy. I\u2019m willing to bet that many people who consider themselves Queen fans do so on the basis of that album and have never listened to the original albums from which they were drawn. If they had they\u2019d realise that they had more breadth than their singalong hits suggest (see \u201cSheer Heart Attack\u201d for one of their best) and I\u2019ve never met a self-declared fan who\u2019s proved me wrong on that charge. Of course radio play doesn\u2019t help but it does nothing to say that they were anything better than Bohemian Rhapsody or We Will Rock You when there are so many hidden gems waiting to be discovered. So, for everyone who just owns the greatest hits, buy the original bloody albums and appreciate the full band - especially John Deacon who wrote more hits than Freddie Mercury ever did. ",
