                "name": "Lilani van Deventer",
                "href": "/profile/Lilani-van-Deventer"
            },
            "answer_text": "The answer is quite simple, it was an incredibly hot day. It was the hottest day of that summer, according to the Live Aid documentary. Freddie always placed a lot of effort into his performances. If you watch Queen live at the Bowl (Milton Keynes 1982), you will see that Freddie is as sweaty as he was on the Live Aid performance, after a few songs. Although, some people have noticed that Freddie had marks on his arm, which could have been Kaposi sarcoma. Kaposi sarcoma Is one of the first or most obvious signs of Aids, it is a type of skin cancer, that can effect your internal organs, throat, mouth, nose and obviously your skin. You can see a bruise on Freddie\u2019s arm, just above the arm band. But, it is speculation, it could just have been a normal bruise.  Edit, to add that Kaposi Sarcoma legions doesn\u2019t just disappear. The bruise on Freddie\u2019s arm could not be seen during the Magic tour. Therefore it was probably just a bruise. ",
